### SSR Benefits

Server-Side Rendering (SSR) renders Vue components on the server and sends fully rendered HTML to the client:

- **SEO**: Search engines can crawl fully rendered content
- **Performance**: Users see content faster (no JS download required for first paint)
- **Social sharing**: Social media previews (OG tags) work properly
- **Accessibility**: Content is available even if JavaScript fails

### useHead for SEO

Nuxt provides `useHead` to manage meta tags for each page:

```vue
<script setup>
useHead({
  title: 'About Us - My Site',
  meta: [
    { name: 'description', content: 'Learn about our company' },
    { property: 'og:title', content: 'About Us' },
    { property: 'og:image', content: '/og-image.png' }
  ]
})
</script>
```

### Server vs Client Code

Nuxt runs code on both server and client. Use these patterns to distinguish:

```vue
<script setup>
// Runs on server then client (hydration)
const { data } = await useFetch('/api/data')

// Client-only
if (process.client) {
  console.log('Running in browser')
  localStorage.setItem('visited', 'true')
}

// Server-only
if (process.server) {
  console.log('Running on server')
  // Access filesystem, database, etc.
}
</script>
```

### Hybrid Rendering

Nuxt 3 supports hybrid rendering — different routes can use different modes:

```ts
// nuxt.config.ts
export default defineNuxtConfig({
  routeRules: {
    '/': { prerender: true },                    // SSG
    '/blog/**': { ssr: true },                   // SSR
    '/dashboard/**': { ssr: false },             // SPA
    '/api/**': { cors: true }                    // API routes
  }
})
```

This allows you to optimize each route for its specific needs.
